Date: Wed, 13 May 2026 15:13:26 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 7/7] ALSA: hda/realtek: enable AW88399 on Lenovo Legion Pro
 5/7

Enable audio output through the AW88399 woofer amplifiers on Lenovo
Legion Pro 5/7 laptops by adding the necessary Realtek ALC287 fixups
and AW88399 property quirks.

Realtek fixups (alc269.c):

- ALC287_FIXUP_AW88399_I2C_2: registers the AW88399 as a two-instance
  I2C companion codec using comp_generic_fixup, matching ACPI HID
  AWDZ8399.

- ALC287_FIXUP_LENOVO_LEGION_AW88399: overrides the bass speaker pin
  0x17 configuration (wrongly reported as unconnected on some models)
  and forces DAC 0x02, as the default DAC 0x06 lacks volume controls.
  Also applies internal microphone boost calibration via
  alc269_fixup_limit_int_mic_boost and disables unused pin 0x1d.
  Chained to ALC287_FIXUP_AW88399_I2C_2.

AW88399 property quirks (aw88399_hda_property.c):

- Channel swap: the I2C wiring on these Legion models is reversed
  (0x34 is physically the right speaker, 0x35 is the left). The
  quirk swaps the channel assignment to correct L/R audio.

- BSTS status bypass: the AW88399's boost-finished status bit (BSTS,
  SYSST register bit 9) does not reliably assert on this hardware.
  Register dumps during normal playback show both amplifiers in active
  boost mode (ADPS=1, bit 13) with BSTS=0 on both channels, despite
  clean audio output. The quirk sets the bsts_unreliable flag
  (introduced in patch 4) so the startup status check skips the BSTS
  requirement on these devices.

Supported models (Lenovo vendor ID 0x17aa):

- 0x3906: Legion Pro 7i 16IAX10H (Intel)
- 0x3907: Legion Pro 7i 16IAX10H (Intel)
- 0x3908: Legion Pro 5 16IAX10H (Intel)
- 0x3938: Legion Pro 7 16AFR10H (AMD)
- 0x3939: Legion Pro 7 16AFR10H (AMD)
- 0x3d6c: Legion Pro 7i 16IAX10H / Y9000P IAX10 (Intel)
